The next line will connect any two points on the original line.<n>The next part of the sequence will be formed by adding and subtracting.<n><n>### Instrument : <n><n><n><n>###Instructions: Draw any number of lines that pass through the red dot. Make each line a different size. The next line will <n>always pass through the blue dot. The next part of the sequence is a series of different numbers<n> <n>##Instructions:<n><n>## Instruction: Draw an even number of lines and connect the dots.  Draw another line that will connect any dot to its neighbor (on either side) on every line  drawn in the first part.<n><n>## Instuctions:<n><n>###Instruction: There are several rules that explain how to find the next number in a sequence of number.

Remember to include your logic.<n>  <n>What is wrong with this program's output?<n><n>```python<n>input:<n>	1 + 2 - 3<n><n>output:<n>	7<n>```<n>### Answer:<n><n>It appears that we should multiply 2 and 3, or 2x3 or 3*2.<n><n><n>```python<n>    def doTheMaths(num1, num2) :<n>	#do the maths!<n>	if num1 == num2:<n>		return(num1 * num2)<n>	elif (num1 > num2):<n>		return(doTheMaths(num2, num1))<n>```<n><n>### Solution:<n>```python<n>    DoTheMaths = lambda x,y: doTheMaths(x,y) <n>	 <n>    input = <n>    "Input x, y and you will receive the product:"<n>	  <n>    x = int(input("Enter x: "))<n>	  <n>    y = int(input("x:"))<n>	  <n>    mymath = <n>    "DoTheMaths(x+y)"<n>	 <n>    print(mymath)<n>```<n><n>## Solution for 10:<n>```python<n>	input :<n>	50  +  20  -  20<n><n>	2<n><n>	input :<n><n>	do the maths:<n>	3<n><n>	7<n><n>	input :    <n><n>	50   +  20   -  20   ===>   (50 + 20) - 20<n>	50   ===>  ____________    + 20<n>	360   ===> - 20   (do something wrong)<n><n>	480   ===> _____________     - 20<n><n>	4<n><n>	3<n>```<n><n>## Question:<n><n>### Instruction : Answer the question below. What game are they playing? His wife was raising two children, and this only increased her workload. It put her under a lot of stress.  What might this lead to? Choices:  A: asthma B: more C: boredom D: headache E: arguments<n>Output: E: arguments<n><n>Input: How will a teacher begin projects for students required to work together? Choices:  A: medical building B: hospital C: school D: strip mall E: urban area<n>Output: D: strip mall<n><n>Input: What would dogs do if there are no intruders nearby? Choices:  A: theft B: sleep soundly C: do many things D: go outside E: many colours<n>Output: B: sleep soundly<n><n>Input: Where is the best place to get a bicycle for a child? Choices:  A: toy store B: fun C: street D: university E: garage<n>Output: A: toy store<n><n>Input:What common chemical reaction is often used as a heat source? Choices:  A: coal or wood B: fire C: lava D: house E: solar energy<n>Output:		B: fire<n><n>Input:What do we use in computers to store pictures? Choices:  a) a computer  b) the internet  c) a mouse  d) all of these  e) a monitor<n>Output: E: a monitor<n><n>Input:What tool is used for doing small tasks such as sewing? Choices:  B) knife  C) a hand drill  D) sewing machine  E) fork<n>Output: E: sewing machine<n><n>Input: Which type of tool is most useful for making large cuts in wood or for splitting wood? Choices: 0) Knife 1) Hand drill 2) scraping tool 3) sewing machine 4) 6mm drill 5) saw<n>Output: 5) Saw<n><n>### Source Code:<n><n>```python<n>input = "Where do humans go in cities like London to be in nature?";<n>input = input.split(" ");<n>input = input[1];<n>answers = ["A: movie theatre", "B: university", "C: park", "D: alaska", "E: country"];<n># Find the key for a match, else match is None<n>key = [ans for n in input.replace(" ", '') for ans in answers];<n>answer = ["C: park"];<n>print (key);<n>print(answer);<n>```<n><n>### Submission Link:<n><n>[https://www.hackerrank.com/contests/woc/challenges/instruction](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/algorithms/searching/index/instruction)<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Where do humans go in cities to be in nature? The main character is John Worthing, who takes the name Ernest because, as he puts it in “The Importance of Being Earnest”(IPE): “No one in the world is called Ernest”. He is a confirmed bachelor who must maintain the lies he made up so that he could take the name Ernest. His best friend is Lord Jack. At first glance Worthing seems like a good person, but his personality is a blend of a good and flawed person. Throughout the play he does a lot of selfish things out of his love for Algernon who is in love with another woman named Cecily, which is the daughter of Worthing’s “Aunt Augusta”. Worthing’s brother, Algernon Moncrieff is also the main character. He is in love with Gwendoly and they seem like they will be perfect together. But Gwendily is also in love with Cecily although she does not know it. Her name was originally Ernest by her old governess who wanted to make sure no one called her Ernest. This is one of the major themes of the play.<n>"The Importance of Being Ernust" is a 1895 play written by British dramatist Oscar Wilde.<n><n>The storyline is centered on four main characters and each of them have different characteristics. Algernon who is the brother of John Worthing is in love with Gwinodry Cardew although she does not know in a way. He is also in love with an 18-year-old girl named Cecily, who is the daughter of John Worthing’s Aunt Augusta. John Worthing who owns his own house takes the name Ernest. When talking to his other friend Lord Jack, he lies to him

But that is about to change thanks to an emerging sociopolitical movement led by the millennial generation. "It is no longer socially acceptable to be so loose and cavalier with how we use the word 'friend," explains 27-year-old Cara Anderson.  "If you're old enough to have a social media account, you're old enough not to have so many 'friends'" she says. "We're being forced to grow up. The world doesn't revolve around us anymore." Anderson, an early pioneer of the growing anti-friendship movement, is quick to note that she isn't "anti-friendship in the classic sense of the word".  She explains, "We still need other people in our lives to fill different roles. Just not all at the same time!" Which best expresses (for better or worse) this movement?   Choices:  A.) Choices:  A: sporting event B: time race C: part two boxers D: football E: hockey game<n>Output: E: hockey game<n><n>Input: What kind of breathing makes noise but does not indicate that you are sick? Choices:  A: sigh B: clavicular C: yawn D: cough E: live<n>Output: A: sigh<n><n>Input: What do you wear on the bridge of your nose? His wife was raising two children, and this only increased her workload. It put her under a lot of stress.  What might this lead to? Choices:  A: asthma B: more C: boredom D: headache E: arguments<n>Output: E: arguments<n><n>Input: How will a teacher begin projects for students required to work together? Choices:  A: state facts B: teach pupils C: group students D: better knowledge E: dividing students<n>Output: C: group students<n><n>Input: It seemed weird to have a dental office located next to a candy store and fast food location at the what? Choices:  A: medical building B: hospital C: school D: strip mall E: urban area<n>Output: D: strip mall<n><n>Input: What would dogs do if there are no intruders nearby? Choices:  A: theft B: sleep soundly C: do many things D: go outside E: many colours<n>Output: B: sleep soundly<n><n>Input: Where is the best place to get a bicycle for a child? Choices:  A: toy store B: fun C: street D: university E: garage<n>Output: A: toy store<n><n>Input:Where could you find a fox hunting when not in a forest? Choices:  A: open meadow B: arctic tundra C: beach D: great outdoors E: england<n>Output:		D: great outdoours<n><n>You are given an integer N. Return a list of strings, each of the length N, such that every element of the list is the concatenation of the elements of the corresponding previous element.<n><n>Input: [2, 3, 4]<n>Output: ["a", "aa", "aaa"]<n><n>#### Solution<n><n>import math<n><n>def concat(lst, c=', '):<n>	"""<n>	Returns an array of size lst[0] + lst[1]+ ... + lst[N-1]<n>	"""<n><n>	if lst[0] == '': return lst[1:]+c+lst[2:]<n>	return c+lst[0]+''+concat(lst[1:], c)<n><n>def f(N):<n>	if N <= 0:<n>		return [[]]<n>	if len(range(3, N+1))>1:<n>		return [[concat(range(N-n, n+1), ', ')[n:]] for n in range(3, N+2)]<n>	else:<n>		return range(N), True

When the boy's father asks him about how he can get him involved in a particular event, the boy replies that they have different schedules. His father then comes up with the idea of using texts to communicate more efficiently. The boy appreciates the father's support and decides to join the event.<n><n>Question2: Do you think texts are easier or more time-consuming?<n><n>My answer: It depends on the context of the conversation. If the text is for informal purposes and the topic is not too serious then it can be done a few times but if the text is for formal purposes it might be more time-consuming.

A full-size picture would include all items, including the background. The second quality concerns how detailed the camera will be. The answer is a "C: park" which stands for choice option C or you can say there is a probability of 1/5 that that choice is correct<n><n>**In the first question I was trying to find out the probability of getting a correct choice**.<n><n>For a better understanding take a look at this visual<n><img src="../assets-ug.jpg"/><n><n>**In the second question I was trying to get the probability which is getting closer to the probability of the first question.**<n><n>**In the third question I had a 1/3 probability of getting closer to the answer I wanted to get. I did the same thing.**<n><n>**If it is very hard for you I am going to show you with the probability how to solve the problems.**<n><n>First answer have the 1/4 as a probability to get and the second choice the 1/3 as a probability to get.<n><n>That way you can start to find out different probability.<n><n>Let's take an example where we find out the probability of choosing the first letter.<n><n>**There are three letters** and the probability to choose the first one is 1/3 with our current algorithm we got the chance to choose the second and third letter.<n><n>1/3 -> 1/2 -> 1/4 ->... -> (1/x)->(1/x)/3 -> 1/6....<n><n>That shows that you can find out the different probabilities with each new answer.<n><n>### Bonus

Choices:  (no words given)<n>Output: A: intersection<n><n><n>### Instruction: Answer the following extended response questions.<n><n>What do you know about the difference between formal and informal speech?<n><n>### Instructions:<n><n>The difference between formal and informational speech is the kind of audience that each type of speech is intended for and how they each use grammar rules. Informal speech is informal and is used mostly in personal settings, such as between family and friends. It uses many idioms and informalities, but is still grammatically correct. Formal speech is intended mostly for official settings and is usually longer and more detailed. It consists of formal structures and appropriate grammar.<n><n>### Instructuion:<n><n>To make it easier, you can go to http://www.diffen.com/difference/Informal_Language_vs_Formal_Language to look at it more in depth.<n><n>### Your submission<n>1.)In my opinion, "I" is a very informal way to start off a letter. I understand that it is short and doesn't take any time to read, but many people still feel uncomfortable with it.<n><n>I think this is a good and clear example of the difference between formal and formal speech. When the teacher is writing something, they write very formally and it tends to be more detailed than normal. The use of "I" instead of "We" is also an example of the difference between informal and formal.<n><n>### What will help you keep the differences in between these two groups from blending together in your own writing? (10 points )<n>To keep the speeches from blending together, remember to ask yourself, "how can I use more formal language in this setting?" I feel like the more times that you consider using more formal in writing, the more you will become used to it and notice it in your own writing.<n><n>
